etymologies: mid 18th century; earliest use found in Jonathan Edwards (1703–1758), theologian and philosopher. From classical Latin resuscitant-, resuscitans, present participle of resuscitāre resuscitate

definitions: An agent or treatment used for resuscitation.
A person who resuscitates; a resuscitated person.
Of an agent or treatment: used in or relating to resuscitation; having a resuscitating effect; resuscitative.
